This article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring March 2016 as American Red Cross Month. The proclamation highlights the history of the American Red Cross, starting with its founder Clara Barton's efforts to provide care and supplies to wounded soldiers during the Civil War. It acknowledges the work of the American Red Cross in responding to disasters both in the United States and globally, providing relief and assistance to those in need. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of resilience and service in times of tragedy, and encourages Americans to support organizations like the American Red Cross that work to uplift vulnerable communities. The article concludes with the official proclamation by President Obama, urging Americans to observe the month with appropriate programs and activities and to support service and relief organizations.